<TITLE> Malaysia Chinese party chief to shun cabinet job </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KUALA LUMPUR, March 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The leader of Malaysia's main Chinese party in the ruling coalition will not seek a ministerial job following a shocking election setback at the weekend, his party said on Tuesday. The Malaysian Chinese Association (MCA), a key partner in Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi's multi-racial coalition, said the move would help the party rebuild itself after the poll carnage. "To carry out this responsibility, which has become urgent with the latest political developments, I have decided not to nominate myself for the cabinet post, or to take up any government appointments," MCA President Ong Ka Ting said. MCA stood in 40 parliamentary and 90 state seats, but won just 15 and 31 seats respectively, with the opposition taking a clean sweep of all MCA seats in the northern state of Penang. MCA, which had four seats in the last cabinet, had on Monday dismissed speculation it might pull out of the 14-party coalition which has ruled the nation since independence in 1957. The coalition lost the two-thirds majority in parliament it had held for nearly 40 years at the elections as Chinese and Indian voters led a protest vote. The prime minister faced an enormous task ahead in holding together his battered coalition and filling holes in his cabinet -- four ministers lost seats in the election, including Works Minister S. Samy Vellu, the head of the main Indian party in the coalition
